In article <5848@wet.UUCP>, naga@wet.COM (Peter Davidson) writes:
> 
>  
>>From: KEITHWRITERS@delphi.com
>>Subject: Prosody Release Cancelled Under "NSA" Pressure
>>Message-ID: <931112.49291.KEITHWRITERS@delphi.com>
>>
>>Technosys Press Release
>>
>>The scheduled release of Technosys' text composition program Mirrorshades
>>and text revision/encryption program Prosody has been cancelled because of
>>pressure from a governmental group claiming to be the National Security
>>Administration (NSA) wishing to prevent the release of Prosody as an
>>encryption program.
>>
>>The "NSA" has expressed concern over the encryption method used by
>>Prosody. They feel that it may be using an encryption technology similar
>>enough to another method of natural language encryption that Prosody might
>>be able to be used to break that coding method.
>  
> What's this "encryption technology"?  Did you develop it yourself?
> If not, from where did you obtain it?  Have you stolen anyone else's
> intellectual property?	Have you violated any non-disclosure agreement?
> If not, how can you be accused of committing a crime?
>  
>>Since the next step, if Technosys were to refuse [to hand over all
>>relevant materials], would be the seizure of all
>>of the above materials by search warrant and criminal charges,
>  
> A search warrant must be issued by a court after evidence is presented
> to a judge that a crime has been committed or is underway.	What crime?
> What criminal charges were you afraid might be brought?  I was not
> aware that the development or commercial use of encryption software in
> this country is a criminal act.
>  
> If we're going to submit to the wishes of government agencies when
> not required to do so by law then we might as well get on the next
> cattle truck to the nearest labor camp and abandon any idea that we
> are citizens of a free country.
>  
